(1) Solar and Wind to Top Coal Power in US for First Time in 2024 [ https:/=
/www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-12-12/solar-and-wind-to-top-coal-powe=
r-in-us-for-first-time-in-2024 ]
Will Wade for Bloomberg
Electricity generated from US solar and wind systems will surpass power pro=
duced by burning coal for the first time next year, driven by surging panel=
 installations.
Solar cost curves create some of the most beautiful charts [ https://ourwor=
ldindata.org/search?q=3Dsolar%20energy ] in the world. They usually focus o=
n the plummeting cost of solar panels, the exponential growth of solar capa=
city, or solar=E2=80=99s growing share of energy output.  The chart above, =
based on data recently released by the U.S. Energy Information Agency, not =
only captures solar=E2=80=99s massive growth over the last decade, but also=
 showcases coal=E2=80=99s even more dramatic drop-off. Combine the two tren=
ds, and for the first time ever, the U.S. will generate more electricity fr=
om solar and wind than from coal in 2024.=20
We can=E2=80=99t fully credit coal=E2=80=99s demise to renewables, as much =
more of its output has been replaced by oil and gas. But oil and gas, espec=
ially gas, are safer than coal, and gas is much safer. They=E2=80=99re each=
 a little bit cleaner, too. =20
The transition won=E2=80=99t happen overnight, but the crossover is an impo=
rtant step for a nation that was built on coal but will need a lot more sol=
ar, fission, and fusion to progress from here. Speaking of which=E2=80=A6=
=20
(2) Kairos=E2=80=99 Hermes Secures First NRC Green Light for Advanced Nucle=
ar Non-LWR Reactor [ https://www.powermag.com/kairos-hermes-secures-first-n=
rc-green-light-for-advanced-nuclear-non-lwr-reactor/ ]
=E2=80=9CHermes is the first non-water-cooled reactor to be approved for co=
nstruction in the U.S. in over 50 years.=E2=80=9D
Last week, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) approved a construction =
permit for Kairos Power's Hermes molten salt demonstration reactor, marking=
 the first non-water-cooled reactor construction approval in the U.S. in ov=
er 50 years. Most notably, Kairos uses a fluoride salt-cooled high-temperat=
ure reactor (KP-FHR) as opposed to traditional light-water reactors (LWRs).=
 50 years was a long time to wait, and we may have to wait a few more years=
 until we see this technology really impacting life in the US, but it=E2=80=
=99s important for a few reasons.
The NRC hasn=E2=80=99t approved an advanced reactor design since 1973!=20
Advanced reactors [ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Dr_IJ1C_XuQI ] can be =
cheaper and safer than older designs and it=E2=80=99s insane that the NRC h=
as stood in their way.=20
Just another notch on nuclear=E2=80=99s recent momentum.
Let=E2=80=99s keep up this momentum in 2024, NRC!
(3) This GPT-powered robot chemist designs reactions and makes drugs =E2=80=
=94 on its own [ https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-04073-4 ]
Katharine Sanderson for Nature
The system, called Coscientist, can design, code and carry out several reac=
tions =E2=80=94 making compounds including paracetamol and aspirin in the w=
et lab using its robot apparatus.
A team at Carnegie Mellon released =E2=80=9CCoscientist,=E2=80=9D an AI-mod=
el built off of GPT-4 and Anthropic=E2=80=99s models that can autonomously =
design and execute chemical reactions, and has now successfully synthesized=
 compounds such as paracetamol and aspirin. Coscientist can already do many=
 of a chemist=E2=80=99s routine tasks, but in the future, chemistry tools a=
nd hardware will come pre-programmed with software like Coscientists, creat=
ing what one analyst called, =E2=80=9CSelf-driving labs.=E2=80=9D
The crazy stuff will happen at the intersections. Quantum x Fusion. Space x=
 Batteries. Biotech x AI. And of course that crazy stuff will cause some fe=
ar at first, but over time, we=E2=80=99ll look back at the pre-self-driving=
-lab era as quaint and painfully slow.=20
Like, yes please, let=E2=80=99s have an AI working 24/7 researching, design=
ing, and synthesizing compounds that could benefit our health and cure our =
diseases.
(4) Cancer-fighting CAR-T cells could be made inside body with viral inject=
ion [ https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-03969-5 ]
Heidi Ledford for Nature
Researchers are closing in on ways to produce CAR T cells [ https://www.nat=
ure.com/articles/nature.2017.22304 ] in the body, raising hopes that the no=
toriously expensive and bespoke cancer therapies [ https://www.nature.com/a=
rticles/d41586-020-02675-w ] might one day become more accessible.
CAR-T cell therapy is currently used to treat certain types of blood cancer=
s and has shown significant success in patients for whom traditional treatm=
ents were ineffective. There=E2=80=99s a problem, though: CAR-T is notoriou=
sly expensive and thus inaccessible to the vast majority of people.=20
But new research presented this week at a Hematology conference in San Dieg=
o (talk about a bloody good time!) aims to engineer these T cells directly =
inside the body using a virus, potentially simplifying and reducing the cos=
t of the treatment. This more straightforward, less-invasive treatment proc=
esses could open up a whole new avenues of both cancer and other disease tr=
eatments, since it=E2=80=99s less expensive and could be used to target oth=
er types of cells as well.
For more on cell-based therapies, check out Elliot=E2=80=99s [ https://twit=
ter.com/ElliotHershberg ] banger, Medicine=E2=80=99s Endgame [ https://www.=
notboring.co/p/medicines-endgame ].
(5) The Most Secretive Longevity Lab Finally Opens Its Doors [ https://www.=
bloomberg.com/news/features/2023-12-19/longevity-startup-retro-biosciences-=
is-sam-altman-s-shot-at-life-extension ]
Ashlee Vance for Bloomberg
Retro Biosciences, a startup with $180 million from Sam Altman, has a simpl=
e and audacious goal: Add 10 good years to your life. And until now, we hav=
en=E2=80=99t had a glimpse of its best ideas.
2023: The Year of Sama. He=E2=80=99s founded or backed leading companies in=
 AI, fusion, and crypto, among others. Now, he=E2=80=99s unveiling more inf=
ormation about his longevity play, Retro Biosciences.=20
The company=E2=80=99s mission is ambitious: add 10 healthy years to your li=
fe. And its approach is unique, as compared to other biotech companies, in =
that it=E2=80=99s simultaneously working on five projects, instead of focus=
ing all of its resources on one breakout drug. Among those five bets, one i=
s in the removal of damaged cells, one is in the rejuvenation of blood plas=
ma, and three are in cell reprogramming.
Adding 10 years of healthy living would be no small feat. The development o=
f clean water and sanitation in the 19th and 20th centuries added 20-30 yea=
rs of lifespan. Vaccines and antibiotics have raised the average another fe=
w years. Anesthesia made life-extending surgeries possible. And of course, =
general improvements in agriculture and public health have also moved the n=
eedle. If Retro is successful, we can add cell reprogramming to that list.
There=E2=80=99s this weird pressure I feel with the older folks in my life.=
 It=E2=80=99s almost like the pressure to stay healthier longer is compound=
ed by the fact that we seem to be on the precipice of major longevity break=
throughs. Each year they live increases the probability they=E2=80=99ll be =
around for that breakthrough. Anyway, that=E2=80=99s a good pressure to fee=
l and a pressure that we=E2=80=99re uniquely privileged to experience in th=
e year 2023.
Bonus 1: Future=E2=80=99s Bret Adcock shared an amazing thread [ https://tw=
itter.com/adcock_brett/status/1736450188464599216?s=3D20 ] detailing the la=
test news in AI x Robotics. Humanoid robots walking around Berkley, Ilya ex=
plaining why OpenAI isn=E2=80=99t getting into robots, AI news anchors, and=
 a bunch of quiet but important model upgrades.
Bonus 2: Age of Miracles Last Season 1 Episode
Listen on Spotify [ https://open.spotify.com/episode/5aBdiIscs2eqpGnIrdCVP9=
?si=3DctWkm7UUQ4mzq_qrOdKd9w ], Apple [ https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podca=
st/age-of-miracles/id1527421931 ], or YouTube [ https://youtu.be/A2s-1PFo5e=
Y ]!
Packy here. Perfect timing: last Weekly Dose of the year, last episode of A=
ge of Miracles Season 1. And we=E2=80=99re ending on a very optimistic note=
=2E=20
Throughout the season, we covered the history of nuclear fission and fusion=
 energy, discussed the challenges to their widespread adoption, and talked =
to the founders and investors working hard to overcome those challenges. We=
 even let people who think other energy sources, like solar, are the real a=
nswer tell us why we=E2=80=99re wrong.=20
My takeaway from all of this: we need a lot more energy. Solar, wind, geoth=
ermal, oil, and gas will all play a role. But fission and fusion are going =
to be critical if we want energy superabundance, so much energy that we can=
 put most of humanity=E2=80=99s needs =E2=80=9Cbelow the API,=E2=80=9D as C=
asey Handmer [ https://twitter.com/CJHandmer ] put it. =20
So for the last episode, we briefly reflect on the season before sharing so=
me of our favorite guests=E2=80=99 answers to the question: =E2=80=9CWhat w=
ould the world look like if we had abundant energy?=E2=80=9D=20
Creating this season of Age of Miracles with Julia DeWahl [ https://twitter=
=2Ecom/juliadewahl ], Nancy Xu [ https:=
//twitter.com/nncxu ], Amelia Salyers=20=
[ https://twitter.com/ASalyers3 ], the Turpentine [ https://www.turpentine.=
co/ ] team, and our incredible roster of guests has been one of my highligh=
ts of 2023. We=E2=80=99ve gotten over 120k listens so far, and I hope we=E2=
=80=99ve created something evergreen that people can use to get up to speed=
 on what I=E2=80=99ve come to believe is humanity=E2=80=99s most important =
pursuit.=20
We=E2=80=99ll be dropping full-length versions of some of our favorite epis=
odes in the coming weeks while we gear up for season 2. Stay tuned, and whi=
le you=E2=80=99re home for the holidays, I hope you share it to nuke-pill y=
our friends & family.
Happy holidays!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you=E2=80=99re a developer and have so=
me time this weekend, check out Merge [ https://www.merge.dev/sponsorships/=
not-boring?utm_source=3Dnotboring ].
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox in 2024.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

